      <div rendition="class:83225 maturity:83211" type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn">
        <ab><lb n="01"/>siddham</ab>
        <!--
Siddham is written on the left margin, just before the beginning of line 3.
-->
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="1">
          <l n="a"><lb n="1"/><unclear>ya</unclear>d a<unclear>ṁ</unclear>tar-jjyotir arkkābham</l>
          <l n="b">u<unclear>r</unclear>vvy<unclear>ā</unclear><supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->m</supplied> <seg met="==-+-=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg><!--
Bhandarkar suggests urvvyām asulabhaṁ nr̥ṣu. Sircar: urvvyāṁ bhāti nirantaram. Willis (2009, with suggestions from Whitney Cox and Hans Bakker): urvvyāṁ tu durlabhaṁ nr̥ṣu.
--></l>
          <l n="c"><seg met="====-+">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> -vyāpi</l>
          <l n="d">candragu<unclear>ptākhya</unclear>m adbhutaM <num value="1">1</num><!--
Bhandarkar suggests tat sudhī-hr̥daya-vyāpi for the lacuna (Willis accepts). Sircar: divā-vibhāvarī-vyāpi.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="2">
          <l n="a"><lb n="2"/>vikramāvakraya-krītā</l>
          <l n="b">dāsya-nyagbhūta-<unclear>pā</unclear>rtthiv<unclear>ā</unclear></l>
          <l n="c"><seg met="===">
              <gap quantity="3" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> m anusaṁraktā</l>
          <l n="d">dharmma <seg met="==-+-=">
              <gap quantity="6" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> <num value="2">2</num><!--
Note Fleet reads mānasaṁraktā; Bhandarkar is says it looks more like m anu and conjectures pr̥thvī yam anusaṁraktā and dharma-san-naya-pālitā for the lacunae. The u mātrā under n is indeed quite conspicuous, unlikely to be a flaw in the rock. Sircar suggests the restoration yasya śāsana-saṁraktā dharmajñasya vasundharā.
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="3">
          <l n="a"><lb n="3"/>tasya rājādhirājarṣer</l>
          <l n="b">acin<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->t</supplied>yo <seg met="=-">
              <gap quantity="2" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> <supplied cert="low" reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->ka</supplied>rmmaṇaḥ<!--
Fleet suggests acintyojjvala or acintyoddhata (but where? not in CII3, that I can see); Bhandarkar votes for acintyodāra.
--></l>
          <l n="c">anvaya-prāpta-sācivyo</l>
          <l n="d">vyā <seg met="==">
              <gap quantity="2" reason="illegible" unit="character"/>
            </seg> <supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->san</supplied>dh<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->i</supplied>v<supplied reason="lost"><!-- CHECK if <unclear> applies better.-->i</supplied>grah<unclear>e</unclear> <num value="3">3</num><!--
Fleet restores the lacuna as vyāpr̥tasandhivigrahaḥ; Bhandarkar says this makes no sense and is unmetrical to boot (as pointed out already by Bühler; the second and the third syllable is not supposed to be simultaneously short). Bhandarkar conjectures vyāsr̥ṣṭas sandhivigrahe
--></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="4">
          <l n="a"><lb n="4"/>kautsaś śāba Iti khyāto</l>
          <l n="b">vīrasenaḥ kulākhyayā</l>
          <l n="c">śabdārttha-nyāya-loka-jñaẖ</l>
          <l n="d">kaviḫ pāṭaliputrakaḥ <num value="4">4</num></l>
        </lg>
        <lg met="anuṣṭubh" n="5">
          <l n="a"><lb n="5"/>kr̥tsna-pr̥thvī-jayārtthena</l>
          <l n="b">rājñaiveha sahāgataḥ</l>
          <l n="c">bhaktyā bhagavataś śambhor</l>
          <l n="d">gguhām etām akāraya<unclear>T</unclear> <num value="5">
              <unclear>5</unclear>
            </num></l>
        </lg>
